Truth‑Convergent Autonomy:

A Paradigm for Reliable Knowledge Acquisition in Extreme Environments

PhD Proposal (Final, Theory‑Only Version)
Author: Ouadi Maakoul
Date: March 2026
Status: Complete Submission – Theoretical Focus

---

Abstract

Autonomous exploration systems are traditionally designed to maximize reward—distance traversed, samples collected, or heuristic scientific value. However, such systems can achieve high performance while maintaining fundamentally incorrect beliefs about their environment, a critical failure mode in high‑stakes domains such as lunar exploration. This proposal introduces Truth‑Convergent Autonomy (TCA) , a new paradigm in which autonomous agents are explicitly designed to minimize epistemic error—the divergence between an agent’s belief and the true state of the world. We instantiate this paradigm through Epistemic Control Systems (ECS) , agents that optimize Expected Information Gain (EIG) to drive belief convergence.

We prove that under a coverage condition, EIG‑maximizing policies yield exponential decay of posterior entropy, guaranteeing efficient convergence toward ground truth. We extend this framework to multi‑agent systems using an adaptive Logarithmic Opinion Pool (LogPool) , shown to be the information‑geometric centroid of beliefs and robust to faulty agents. The proposed system integrates factored Bayesian belief representations, non‑myopic planning via Monte Carlo Tree Search (MCTS), and robust decentralized belief fusion. We further introduce Epistemic Risk, enabling agents to prioritize uncertainty in safety‑critical regions.

All claims are supported by rigorous proofs and analytic comparisons to prior information‑theoretic methods. This work establishes a new mathematical foundation for autonomous systems: not as reward optimizers, but as truth‑seeking agents operating under uncertainty.

