Chapter 4: Multi‑Agent Epistemic Control & Information‑Geometric Fusion

4.1 Decentralized Belief Fusion

For a team of N agents, each maintains its own belief b^i_t(\theta) based on local observations. Communication is intermittent and bandwidth‑limited. We adopt a decentralized fusion approach using an adaptive Logarithmic Opinion Pool (LogPool).

The fused belief at agent i is

b_{\text{fused}}^{(i)}(\theta) \propto \prod_{j=1}^{N} b^j(\theta)^{w_{ij}},

where the weights w_{ij} are non‑negative and sum to 1 for each i. To ensure robustness, we set weights proportional to the inverse entropy of the communicating agent’s belief:

w_{ij} \propto \frac{1}{H(b^j)} \quad \text{(or zero if agent \(j\) is faulty or not communicating)}.

Handling Conflicting Certainty.
In the extreme case where two agents have disjoint supports (e.g., one is absolutely certain it is at location X and another at Y), the product becomes zero everywhere. To avoid a degenerate fused belief, we incorporate an epsilon floor on each distribution (e.g., add a small uniform component) and rely on the adaptive weights: if both agents are highly confident, their entropies are low, so their weights are high; this signals a conflict that would trigger a consistency check or a sensor‑health prior. In practice, the weights can be further modulated by a trust metric to prevent such contradictions from corrupting the fusion.

4.2 Information‑Geometric Interpretation

Theorem 4 (LogPool as Fréchet Mean under Reverse KL).
The fused belief given by the LogPool minimizes the weighted sum of reverse Kullback‑Leibler divergences:

b_{\text{fused}} = \arg\min_{b} \sum_{j} w_{ij} D_{\text{KL}}(b \parallel b^j).

Proof. Minimizing \sum_j w_j \int b(\theta) \log\frac{b(\theta)}{b^j(\theta)} d\theta subject to \int b=1 leads to the log‑pool via Lagrange multipliers. ∎

4.3 Quantitative Robustness to Faulty Agents

Proposition 4 (Quantitative Robustness).
Suppose one agent k is faulty, i.e., its belief b^k is such that the total variation distance to the true distribution \delta_{\theta^*} satisfies \mathrm{TV}(b^k, \delta_{\theta^*}) \ge \varepsilon > 0, while all other agents have beliefs within \delta of \delta_{\theta^*}. Then the weight assigned to agent k is w_{ik} \propto 1/H(b^k). For any fixed \varepsilon, the fused belief satisfies

D_{\text{KL}}(b_{\text{fused}} \parallel b_{\mathrm{healthy}}) \le O\left( \frac{\varepsilon}{H(b^k)} \log N \right),

where the constant depends on the minimum entropy of healthy agents. In particular, as H(b^k) \to \infty (the faulty agent becomes uniform), its influence vanishes.

Proof sketch. Use Pinsker’s inequality to relate total variation to KL, and the fact that the reverse KL is linear in the weights. The product structure of LogPool implies that the fused belief is a weighted geometric mean; the contribution of the faulty agent is dampened by its entropy. ∎

4.4 Comparison with Linear Opinion Pool

The Linear Opinion Pool (arithmetic mean) minimizes a weighted sum of forward KL divergences \sum w_j D_{\text{KL}}(b^j \parallel b) (or equivalently, maximizes expected log score). It is simpler but can produce overconfident fused beliefs and is highly sensitive to outliers. In contrast, LogPool is externally Bayesian (the pool of posterior distributions is the posterior of the pooled prior) and yields a conservative (higher entropy) fusion, which is safer in high‑stakes domains.

