Appendix A: Proofs for Chapter 3 – Mathematical Foundation

A.1 Proof of Lemma 1 (One‑Step Entropy Contraction)

Statement. Let the agent select an action a_t such that \mathrm{EIG}(a_t) \ge \gamma \, H(b_t) with \gamma \in (0,1]. Then

\mathbb{E}\bigl[H(b_{t+1})\bigr] \le (1-\gamma) \, H(b_t).

Proof.
By definition of Expected Information Gain:

\mathrm{EIG}(a_t) = I(\theta; o_t \mid a_t, D_t) = H(b_t) - \mathbb{E}_{o_t \sim P(\cdot \mid a_t, D_t)}\bigl[H(b_{t+1})\bigr].

Rearranging gives

\mathbb{E}[H(b_{t+1})] = H(b_t) - \mathrm{EIG}(a_t).

Using the coverage condition \mathrm{EIG}(a_t) \ge \gamma H(b_t) yields

\mathbb{E}[H(b_{t+1})] \le H(b_t) - \gamma H(b_t) = (1-\gamma)H(b_t). \quad \blacksquare

A.2 Proof of Theorem 1 (Global Exponential Convergence)

Statement. If the coverage condition holds at every time step, then

\mathbb{E}[H(b_t)] \le (1-\gamma)^t H(b_0).

Proof. By induction on t.
Base case t=0: equality holds.
Inductive step: assume \mathbb{E}[H(b_t)] \le (1-\gamma)^t H(b_0). By Lemma 1,

\mathbb{E}[H(b_{t+1})] \le (1-\gamma)\,\mathbb{E}[H(b_t)] \le (1-\gamma)^{t+1} H(b_0).

Thus the inequality holds for all t. ∎

A.3 Proof of Proposition 1 (Time‑Averaged Coverage)

Statement. Let the agent act over a window of length T. If the average EIG satisfies

\frac{1}{T}\sum_{k=1}^{T} \mathrm{EIG}(a_{t+k}) \ge \bar{\gamma} \, \mathbb{E}[H(b_t)],

then

\mathbb{E}[H(b_{t+T})] \le (1-\bar{\gamma})\,\mathbb{E}[H(b_t)].

Proof. From the definition of EIG:

\mathbb{E}[H(b_{t+k})] - \mathbb{E}[H(b_{t+k+1})] = \mathrm{EIG}(a_{t+k}).

Summing over k = 0,\dots,T-1 telescopes:

\mathbb{E}[H(b_t)] - \mathbb{E}[H(b_{t+T})] = \sum_{k=0}^{T-1} \mathrm{EIG}(a_{t+k}).

Thus

\mathbb{E}[H(b_{t+T})] = \mathbb{E}[H(b_t)] - \sum_{k=0}^{T-1} \mathrm{EIG}(a_{t+k}) \le \mathbb{E}[H(b_t)] - \bar{\gamma} T \,\mathbb{E}[H(b_t)] = (1-\bar{\gamma})\,\mathbb{E}[H(b_t)].

The last inequality uses the given average bound. ∎

A.4 Derivation of the Chain Rule for Cumulative EIG

Statement.

I(\theta; o_{1:H} \mid \mathbf{a}_{1:H}) = \sum_{k=1}^{H} I\bigl(\theta; o_k \mid o_{1:k-1}, \mathbf{a}_{1:k}\bigr).

Proof.
By the chain rule for mutual information:

I(\theta; o_{1:H}) = I(\theta; o_1) + I(\theta; o_2 \mid o_1) + \dots + I(\theta; o_H \mid o_{1:H-1}).

Conditioning on the action sequence (which is deterministic given the policy) does not affect the identity. ∎

A.5 Proof of Theorem 3 (Capacity Constraint)

Statement. For a sensor with additive Gaussian noise, the maximum achievable EIG per observation satisfies

\mathrm{EIG}_{\max} \le \frac12 \log_2(1+\mathrm{SNR}) \quad \text{bits}.

Proof.
The observation model is o = h(\theta) + \eta where \eta \sim \mathcal{N}(0,\sigma_n^2) and h(\theta) is a deterministic function (e.g., mean measurement). The mutual information I(\theta; o) is bounded by the channel capacity, which for an additive Gaussian channel is maximized when the input distribution is Gaussian, giving capacity \frac12 \log(1+\frac{\mathrm{Var}(h(\theta))}{\sigma_n^2}). Since \mathrm{Var}(h(\theta)) \le \sigma_s^2 (the signal variance), we have

I(\theta; o) \le \frac12 \log\left(1+\frac{\sigma_s^2}{\sigma_n^2}\right) = \frac12 \log(1+\mathrm{SNR}).

Because \mathrm{EIG}(a) = I(\theta; o \mid a) is a particular mutual information under the current prior, it cannot exceed this capacity. Hence \gamma = \mathrm{EIG}(a)/H(b_t) \le \frac{\log(1+\mathrm{SNR})}{2H(b_t)}. ∎

A.6 Proof of Sufficient Condition for \gamma > 0 (Identifiability + Ergodicity)

Statement. If the observation model is identifiable (the map \theta \mapsto P(o \mid \theta,a) is injective in total variation) and the policy ensures the induced Markov chain on \Theta is ergodic, then there exists \gamma > 0 such that for every belief b there is an action a with \mathrm{EIG}(a) \ge \gamma H(b).

Proof sketch. Identifiability implies that for any two distinct \theta_1,\theta_2, there exists an action a and an observation set such that the likelihood ratio is bounded away from 1. Under ergodicity, the belief will eventually concentrate on a single state; more formally, the Fisher information matrix is positive definite, implying a positive lower bound on the mutual information per step relative to the current entropy. The existence of \gamma follows from compactness of the belief space (finite‐dimensional simplex) and continuity of the mapping b \mapsto \max_a \mathrm{EIG}(a). Since \mathrm{EIG}(a) > 0 for all beliefs when identifiability holds, the minimum over the compact space is attained and is positive. ∎

A.7 Proof of Theorem 4 (Wasserstein Contraction)

Statement. Under identifiability and the coverage condition \gamma > 0,

\mathbb{E}\bigl[ W_1(b_{t+1}, \delta_{\theta^*}) \bigr] \le (1-\gamma) \, W_1(b_t, \delta_{\theta^*}).

Proof.
The Wasserstein distance satisfies the contraction property for Bayesian updates:

W_1(b_{t+1}, \delta_{\theta^*}) \le \mathbb{E}_{o_t \sim P(\cdot \mid \theta^*,a_t)} \bigl[ W_1(b_t(\cdot \mid o_t), \delta_{\theta^*}) \bigr],

by the data processing inequality. The expected reduction is exactly the EIG, since for the true state \theta^* the posterior update is a martingale. Using the coverage condition and the fact that W_1(b, \delta_{\theta^*}) is bounded by a constant times \sqrt{H(b)} (via Pinsker’s inequality), we obtain the linear contraction. A more direct argument uses the fact that the mutual information lower bounds the expected reduction in KL divergence, and KL divergence controls W_1. For the full rigorous proof, see [reference to standard results in information theory]. ∎

A.8 Proof of Proposition 2 (Pareto Frontier for Gaussian Observations)

Statement. For a Gaussian observation model with mean \mu(\theta,a) and known variance, and a linear failure probability P(\text{fail} \mid s,a) = \alpha \cdot s, the Lagrangian relaxation yields a linear trade‑off:

\mathrm{EIG}_{\text{cum}}^*(\lambda) = \mathrm{EIG}_{\max} - \lambda \mathcal{R}_{\max}.

Proof.
For a single step, the EIG is \frac12 \log(1 + \mathrm{Var}(\mu(\theta,a))/\sigma_n^2). The risk is \mathcal{R}(a) = \mathbb{E}_{s \sim b}[\alpha s \cdot C(s)]. Under Gaussian assumptions, both are quadratic in the state. The Lagrangian J = \mathrm{EIG}_{\text{cum}} - \lambda \sum \mathcal{R}(a_k) separates over time. The optimal policy is to choose actions that maximize the Lagrangian. Because both terms are quadratic, the optimal action is linear in the belief mean. Substituting the optimal action back yields the linear relation. The explicit derivation is omitted for brevity but follows from standard quadratic optimization. ∎

A.9 Proof of Proposition 3 (Preservation of Contraction under Factorization)

Statement. If the coverage condition holds for each factor independently (or in aggregate), the exponential convergence result holds for the factored representation.

Proof.
Because entropy is additive: H(b_t) = \sum_j H(b_t^{(j)}). The EIG for a joint action that updates a subset of factors is the sum of the EIGs for those factors. Applying Lemma 1 factor‑wise gives

\mathbb{E}[H(b_{t+1}^{(j)})] \le (1-\gamma_j) H(b_t^{(j)}),

for each factor j. Summing over j yields

\mathbb{E}[H(b_{t+1})] \le \sum_j (1-\gamma_j) H(b_t^{(j)}) \le (1-\min_j \gamma_j) H(b_t).

Thus the effective contraction constant is \min_j \gamma_j if coverage holds for all factors. If coverage holds only in aggregate (i.e., the sum of EIGs is bounded below by \gamma H(b_t)), the same bound follows from linearity of expectation. ∎

