Appendix B: Proofs for Chapter 4 – Multi‑Agent Fusion

B.1 Proof of Theorem 4 (LogPool as Fréchet Mean under Reverse KL)

Statement.

b_{\text{fused}} = \arg\min_{b} \sum_i w_i D_{\text{KL}}(b \parallel b^i).

Proof.
Minimize F(b) = \sum_i w_i \int b(\theta) \log\frac{b(\theta)}{b^i(\theta)} d\theta subject to \int b(\theta)d\theta = 1.
Form the Lagrangian:

\mathcal{L} = \sum_i w_i \int b(\theta) \log\frac{b(\theta)}{b^i(\theta)} d\theta + \lambda \left( \int b(\theta)d\theta - 1 \right).
\]  

Take the functional derivative with respect to b(\theta) and set to zero:

\frac{\delta \mathcal{L}}{\delta b(\theta)} = \sum_i w_i \left( \log\frac{b(\theta)}{b^i(\theta)} + 1 \right) + \lambda = 0.
\]  

Solve for \log b(\theta):

\log b(\theta) = \frac{-\lambda - \sum_i w_i}{\sum_i w_i} + \frac{\sum_i w_i \log b^i(\theta)}{\sum_i w_i}.
\]  

Exponentiating gives

b(\theta) = \frac{1}{Z} \prod_i b^i(\theta)^{w_i},
\]  

with Z the normalizing constant. Thus the minimizer is the LogPool. ∎

B.2 Proof of Proposition 4 (Quantitative Robustness)

Statement. Let agent k be faulty with \mathrm{TV}(b^k, \delta_{\theta^*}) \ge \varepsilon > 0 and healthy agents have beliefs within \delta of \delta_{\theta^*}. Then

D_{\text{KL}}(b_{\text{fused}} \parallel b_{\mathrm{healthy}}) \le O\!\left( \frac{\varepsilon}{H(b^k)} \log N \right).

Proof sketch.
The fused belief is b_{\text{fused}} \propto \prod_i b^i(\theta)^{w_i}. Using the reverse KL divergence,

D_{\text{KL}}(b_{\text{fused}} \parallel b^h) = \sum_i w_i \int b_{\text{fused}}(\theta) \log\frac{b^i(\theta)}{b^h(\theta)} d\theta + \log Z.
\]  

For the faulty agent k, the term w_k \int b_{\text{fused}} \log\frac{b^k}{b^h} can be bounded by w_k \cdot \mathrm{TV}(b^k,b^h) (via Pinsker’s inequality). Since w_k \propto 1/H(b^k), the contribution of the faulty agent is O(\varepsilon / H(b^k)). The healthy agents’ contributions are small because their beliefs are close to \delta_{\theta^*}. The normalizer Z is bounded away from zero because the healthy agents have overlapping support. The logarithmic factor \log N arises from the sum over agents. The full derivation uses standard inequalities from information theory. ∎

