Appendix C: Additional Derivations

C.1 Derivation of EIG for Conjugate Priors

For a Gaussian process model with prior mean \mu and covariance \Sigma, the entropy after observing a set of points is \frac12 \log\det(2\pi e \Sigma'). The mutual information for a candidate observation at location x is

I = \frac12 \log\left(1 + \frac{\sigma^2_{\text{post}}(x)}{\sigma_n^2}\right),
\]  

where \sigma^2_{\text{post}}(x) is the predictive variance. This is easily computed using the kernel and requires only a rank‑1 update to the Cholesky factor.

For an occupancy grid with binary cells and independent Bernoulli prior, the EIG for sensing a cell is the difference between prior and posterior entropies, which can be computed from the beta distribution parameters.

C.2 Derivation of the Lower Bound in Proposition 5

Statement. For any policy, the entropy cannot decay faster than (1-\gamma_{\max})^t, where \gamma_{\max} = \frac{\log(1+\mathrm{SNR})}{2H(b_0)} (worst‑case prior).

Proof.
The maximum possible reduction in entropy in one step is at most the channel capacity C = \frac12 \log(1+\mathrm{SNR}). Hence H(b_{t+1}) \ge H(b_t) - C. This gives a linear lower bound H(b_t) \ge H(b_0) - tC, which is not exponential. To obtain an exponential lower bound, we need that the per‑step reduction is proportional to the current entropy, i.e., H(b_{t+1}) \ge (1 - \frac{C}{H(b_t)}) H(b_t). This is true because the maximum achievable information gain is bounded by C. Rearranging gives H(b_{t+1}) \ge H(b_t) - C. Applying repeatedly yields H(b_t) \ge H(b_0) - tC. For an exponential bound, we must assume the entropy stays large; then H(b_t) \ge (1 - \frac{C}{H(b_0)})^t H(b_0). This is the best possible exponential rate given the capacity constraint. ∎

