Appendix D: Counterexample Constructions

D.1 Myopic vs. Non‑Myopic (Counterexample 1)

Define a POMDP with two states \theta_1, \theta_2 and uniform prior.
Actions:

· a_1: observation o \in \{0,1\} with P(o=1|\theta_1,a_1)=0.6, P(o=1|\theta_2,a_1)=0.4.
· a_2: null action, yields no observation (entropy unchanged).
· a_3: observation o \in \{0,1\} with P(o=1|\theta_1,a_3)=1, P(o=1|\theta_2,a_3)=0 (perfect discrimination).

The EIG of a_1 is H(b) - H(b|o) \approx 0.1 bits for uniform prior. The EIG of a_2 is 0. The EIG of a_3 is 1 bit, but it is only available after taking a_2 (a memory constraint).
Myopic EIG always picks a_1, yielding linear entropy decay H_t \approx 1 - 0.1 t.
Non‑myopic with horizon 2 picks a_2 then a_3, yielding entropy 0 after two steps.
Thus non‑myopic planning is strictly superior.

D.2 Faulty Agent Robustness (Counterexample 2)

Consider two agents.
Agent 1 (correct): belief b^1 concentrated on \theta_1 (e.g., Dirac at \theta_1).
Agent 2 (faulty): belief b^2 concentrated on \theta_2 (e.g., Dirac at \theta_2).
Linear opinion pool with equal weights gives b_{\text{lin}} = 0.5\delta_{\theta_1} + 0.5\delta_{\theta_2} – a bimodal, overconfident distribution that assigns zero probability to any other state.
LogPool with any positive weights gives b_{\text{log}} \propto (\delta_{\theta_1})^{w_1} (\delta_{\theta_2})^{w_2}. This product is zero everywhere because the two Diracs have disjoint support, leading to an undefined (or zero) distribution. To resolve, we add a small uniform component \epsilon to each distribution, yielding b_{\text{log}} \propto (\epsilon)^{w_1+w_2-2} \cdot \text{constant}. The fused belief becomes nearly uniform, which correctly reflects the conflict. Adaptive weights based on entropy would down‑weight both agents because they have low entropy, but the conflict still triggers the need for a consistency check. This demonstrates that LogPool is inherently conservative and signals disagreement rather than masking it.